# Product decisions (locked in — don't re-debate)

Last updated: 2026-04-24. When something changes, edit this file.

## Brand & market (from 2026-04-24 strategy session)

- **Market**: USA-only.
- **Two customer lines, one brand**:
  - **Physical SIM line** — local US IoT + mobile customers (PCCW supplier).
  - **Travel eSIM line** — US travelers going abroad (Red Tea / ESIMAccess supplier).
- **Pricing posture**: slight premium over EIOTCLUB / Talksim / Smartsim / Temu. Premium must be justified by the three brand pillars below.
- **Visual design language**: Airalo-inspired (clean, spacious, human, calm palette). NOT EIOTCLUB-style (dense, countdown-heavy, discount-coded). Reason: Airalo's simplicity fits US taste per Jordan.

## Three brand pillars (concrete, testable claims)

1. **Speed — "5G up to 650 Mbps"**
   Phone/tablet SIM plans: first 9 GB at up to 650 Mbps, then throttle to 10 Mbps.
   Most competitors don't publish speed numbers because theirs are lower. This
   is a real differentiator; use it on product pages.
2. **US IP abroad — "Your US apps just work"**
   Red Tea API lets us pick the breakout IP per plan (US vs HK etc.). For the
   US traveler funnel we sell US-IP variants wherever Red Tea offers them, so
   Netflix / Venmo / banking apps continue to see a US source. Airalo does NOT
   do this; it's our travel moat.
3. **Auto APN — "Plug and play, no APN setup"**
   PCCW SIMs auto-provision APN. Amazon reviews on competitor SIMs routinely
   complain about manual APN steps; we eliminate that friction.

Internal (not yet user-facing): **we can remotely control the speed tier per
SIM/plan**. Kept in back pocket for future "boost to 5G" monetization on
camera plans.

## Speed tiers (must match marketing copy exactly)

| Product line | Speed cap | Over-quota behavior |
|---|---|---|
| Phone / tablet / laptop / pocket WiFi (3-net AT&T/Verizon/T-Mobile) | **650 Mbps** for first 9 GB | 10 Mbps after |
| Security + hunting / trail camera (2-net AT&T/Verizon) | **1.5 Mbps** flat (bundled) / **1 Mbps** (top-ups) | stays capped |
| Low-tier IoT — GPS, walkie, POS, smartwatch, e-reader, mower (2-net) | **500 Kbps** flat | stays capped |

**Disclose these caps openly on product pages.** Per Jordan (2026-04-24): honest
pricing = fewer refunds = higher margin. Never hide the cap.

## Unit economics (from 2026-04-24 pricing spreadsheet)

- **SIM cards are sold at or near break-even on Amazon.** Small plans are
  actually NEGATIVE-margin standalone (e.g. 1 GB/30d @ $6.99 = −$6.21/card).
- **Revenue comes from 5 months of top-up recharges.** 70% month-over-month
  retention decay. That is why the activation → top-up → auto-renew funnel
  is the most important thing in the whole product.
- **Amazon is customer acquisition. Our app is the business model.**

## Architecture — marketing site + in-app shell

- Single H5 codebase, two entry modes:
  - `/` and all non-`/app` paths → marketing site (home, country pages,
    device pages, activation, top-up, blog, help, about, contact).
  - `/app/*` → functional customer shell (shop, my-sims, profile, checkout).
- Flutter app's `InAppWebView` loads `/app` directly; marketing is invisible to it.
- Primary domain: **`evairdigital.com`** (not `evair-h5.netlify.app`).
- Netlify stays the host; the `feature/api-integration` branch is the production
  deploy until told otherwise.

## Phase order (agreed 2026-04-24)

1. **Phase 0** — invisible foundation: split routing into `/` vs `/app`,
   repoint Flutter, no UX change yet.
2. **Phase 1** — activation + top-up funnel (highest ROI, because margins
   come from recharges): `/activate?iccid=`, `/top-up?iccid=`, auto-renew
   toggle, transactional emails.
3. **Phase 2** — device-family landing pages for SEO: `/sim/phone`,
   `/sim/camera`, `/sim/iot`, `/travel-esim/[country]`.
4. **Phase 3** — home page (two-door hero, Airalo aesthetic, brand pillars).
5. **Phase 4** — help center + blog.
6. **Phase 5** — in-app physical SIM checkout (retire Amazon dependency).

Do NOT skip ahead. Phase 1 pays for Phases 2–5.

## Auto-renew disclosure (ROSCA + CA SB-313)

Auto-renew is load-bearing for unit economics, so legal compliance must be
bulletproof from day 1:

- Clear pre-purchase disclosure of price, renewal frequency, cancel method
- Explicit, separate opt-in checkbox (not bundled with T&Cs)
- Confirmation email within 24h with cancel link
- One-click cancel (both in-app AND via email link) per CA SB-313
- Renewal reminder email 3–7 days before each renewal

Draft copy lives in `docs/AUTO_RENEW_DISCLOSURE.md` (to be written in Phase 1).

## Catalogue & inventory
- Physical SIMs are **USA-only** right now. Do NOT show a country picker or
  "United States · AT&T · Verizon · T-Mobile" banner in the SIM card section —
  it was removed on 2026-04-24 as redundant (one country = no filtering value).
  Reintroduce a picker only when we add a second country.
- Physical SIM checkout goes through **Amazon Storefront** (external link from
  ShopView). Not in-app Stripe, not Laravel orders. Don't "fix" this without asking.
- eSIM catalogue fetches **only** via the supplier path (`supplierFetchPackages`
  in `services/dataService.ts`). Do NOT reroute through `packageService` — it
  crashed the shop on 2026-04-22 and the regression guard is in
  `.cursor/rules/esim-api-services.mdc`.

## Suppliers
- **eSIM supplier**: Red Tea / ESIMAccess. Live, works.
- **Physical SIM supplier**: PCCW. Credentials currently show
  `401 Distributor is De-activated` — external blocker. UI falls back to local
  DB snapshots gracefully. Don't hide this from Jordan if it regresses.

## App shell
- The Flutter app (`EvairSIM-App`) is a **thin InAppWebView wrapper** around
  the H5 site. Don't propose native screens; every feature ships to H5 first.
- `H5_URL` in `lib/core/constants/app_constants.dart` must point at the
  **`feature/api-integration` Netlify branch**
  (`https://feature-api-integration--evair-h5.netlify.app/`), NOT the `main`
  branch. `main` is the old version; pointing there regresses the app to the
  outdated UI. This has happened twice — do not repeat.

## AI support assistant (`ai/evairAssistant.ts`)
- **No emojis.** Ever. Tone must be professional, welcoming, polite.
- Supplier-aware vocabulary is required (eSIM vs. physical SIM, Red Tea vs.
  PCCW, USA-only for physical).
